node.text:
Check out where we take the trash recovered by our captains and crews in Guatemala! 

Over the last couple weeks, we’ve explored the causes of plastic pollution in Guatemala and shared our strategy for addressing the ocean plastic crisis in this region. Now, we’re taking you behind the scenes of our main operational base in Puerto Barrios, which is the first stop for the trash our crews recover from the ocean.⁠⁠
⁠⁠
Visit the link in our bio to learn more about where we take our recovered trash in Guatemala! 🇬🇹

Are you obsessed with the clean ocean movement? Do you brag about our mission to all your friends? Are you taking steps to reduce your plastic footprint? Do you encourage others to reduce theirs? ⁠⁠

If you answered “Yes!” this is your chance to become a 4ocean Brand Ambassador and earn cash doing what you already do! ⁠⁠
⁠⁠
We're beyond stoked to launch this brand new program that gives YOU the opportunity to grow the clean ocean movement, and earn awesome rewards while doing so. ⁠⁠
⁠⁠
Click the link in our bio to learn more about the 4ocean Brand Ambassador Program and submit your application 📲⁠⁠
⁠⁠

We are honored to join over 550 organizations and advocates encouraging the next presidential administration to take immediate action on plastic pollution through executive action.

We need a #PlasticFreePresident to lead us on the pathway to a plastic free future! 

Visit the link in our bio to learn about the Plastic Free President Action Plan, get involved by signing the petition, and represent the clean ocean movement!

#breakfreefromplastic #plasticpollution #4ocean #oceanplastic

node.text:
We know that cleaning the ocean and empowering individuals to use alternative products is not enough to stop plastic pollution. We must take bold steps to advocate for policy change that will hold brands, manufacturers, and the plastics industry accountable for their significant contributions to the ocean plastic crisis.

We are proud to support the Break Free From Plastic Pollution Act and are calling on every member of the clean ocean movement to join us. The Break Free From Plastic Pollution Act is a comprehensive piece of federal legislation in the U.S. that provides a comprehensive approach to reducing plastic pollution. 
To find out how you can get involved, visit 4ocean.com/breakfree today!

node.title: The Break Free From Plastic Pollution Act needs our support!

Having ongoing support from people in all industries is imperative to the success of the clean ocean movement. Thank you so much to every single person and group who has shared our story with their followers, friends and families over the years.

We appreciate each and every one of you and look forward to fighting for a cleaner ocean with you for many years to come. Onward!

node.text:
We’re partnering with Safe Harbor for cleaner marinas across the country.

Ever since we introduced the 4ocean Harbor Skimmer, it’s been our 
dream to see it used in harbors and marinas around the world. 
Well, today, we’re stoked to announce that our dream is coming true!

Safe Harbor Marinas, the world’s largest owner and operator of marinas, has agreed to install 4ocean Harbor Skimmers in several of their locations across the country.

Our partnership will begin with a pilot program in Florida before ultimately expanding nationwide — a deployment that would likely involve more than 97 locations.

This is HUGE news and would not be possible without the support of our clean ocean movement and people like you! Every time you purchase a 4ocean product, it helps fund the removal of marine debris from the ocean and supports our efforts to develop and install clean ocean technologies around the world.

Everyone has an origin story, and this is ours.

4ocean was founded on the belief that business can be a force for good, and that the actions of individual people, collectively, have the power to change the world.

While the shores of Bali, might be where the idea of 4ocean was constructed by our founders Alex and Andrew, it's the shores of Florida where our business model was first put to the test.

South Florida was our first-ever cleanup division back in January 2017. So over the coming weeks, we’re going to take you behind the scenes of our South Florida Operation as we prepare to share new, exciting, and innovative ways to protect the ocean. 

Stay tuned as we show you how we've been keepin' it clean since '17!

DIRTY COASTLINES ALERT ⚠️ 

The countdown to International Coastal Cleanup Day continues! 

With just 3 days left until the largest global cleanup event of the year, we wanted to get the clean ocean movement amped up by showing you 5️⃣ EXTREMELY dirty coastlines that our crews around the world recently cleaned.

It's estimated that 80% of ocean plastic pollution comes from a land-based source, and it comes in all shapes and sizes - from microplastics to large pieces of debris. This means that no matter where you live in the world, you CAN help fight this crisis by doing a cleanup in your own community this #InternationalCoastalCleanup Day. 

Which coastline featured here is the dirtiest to you? Drop a number 1-5 in the comments below!

#4oceanCleanups #icc #cleanup #coastalcleanup #coastalcleanupday

Our partnership with the Center for Marine Debris Research is having an EPIC impact!

For every Hawai'ian Coral Reef Bracelet sold, we'll donate $1 to @debrisresearch who will use our donation to fund projects that reduce the ecological damage caused by plastic fishing gear on Hawai'i’s reefs.

Together, we will..
• Remove fishing gear like nets, buoys, and traps from Hawaii’s coral reefs and coastlines
• Photo-document and sample recovered gear to determine which fishery it came from
• Support collaborations with other international research organizations to compare data and ensure its reliability
• Publish research findings in peer-reviewed journals to drive awareness and action on plastic pollution
• Examine the feasibility of setting up a program for long-term monitoring and at-sea removal of ghost gear

To learn more about the impact our partnership with CMDR will have, visit the link in our bio!

Are you ready for the largest global cleanup event of the year?

We're just 5 days away from International Coastal Cleanup Day and we couldn't be more excited.

On Saturday September 18th, 4ocean cleanup crews will be joined by our close friends, families, and community members at cleanups in Boca Raton and Miami in Florida and on the island of Oahu in Hawaii.

On top of that, we'll have supporters from all around the world hosting their own cleanups and taking on trash in their local communities. The clean ocean movement is going #Coast2Coast this International Coastal Cleanup Day!

Tell us where you plan to cleanup in the comments below!

#InternationalCoastalCleanup #4oceanCleanups #icc #cleanup #coastalcleanup #coastalcleanupday

Our good friend @TrashCaulin wanted to answer a question we get a lot about BeBot!

💬 Is BeBot safe for marine life & critters in the sand?

➡️ Absolutely! The BeBot was strategically designed to clean the top 10cm of a beach in order to avoid any marine life. It's controlled by our team, so we can avoid any environmentally sensitive areas or hazards, such as nests. 

In addition, it's exceptionally lightweight for a sifting vehicle, and is able to operate while applying exceptionally low pressure on the sand. Its unique tracks allow the BeBot to equally distribute the pressure applied on the sand with a sinking level that is 3 to 5 times lower than a traditional vehicle of the same weight. 

Any living things smaller than the sifter mesh size will simply fall back into the sand without harm. If any critters do make their way through the sifter and into the collection bin, they can be easily removed by hand and safely returned to the environment by our crew member! 

To learn more about the BeBot, which was designed by robotic engineers and deployed by @Poralu_Marine, visit the link in our bio #4ocean #robot #robotics

NEW: The 4ocean Learning Center ✏️ 

Education is crucial to our mission of ending the ocean plastic crisis because it's the one thing that has the power to stop plastic pollution at the source. 

By teaching people about the causes and impacts of plastic pollution, we empower them to change their relationship with plastic and drive positive action on behalf of the ocean.

We created the 4ocean Learning Center because education is something that should be accessible to everyone. It's a resource for teachers, students, businesses, and ocean enthusiasts who want to learn more about the ocean plastic crisis and be part of the solution to ocean plastic pollution. 

Visit the link in our bio to explore all of the resources we have available and check back often to see what’s new!

Tag someone who loves the ocean and loves to learn in the comments below 🌊

#4ocean #robot #robotics

Have you met the BeBot? 🤖 

If you didn't already know, we recently launched this game-changing clean ocean technology! BeBot, short for beach robot, is an eco-friendly device that's specifically designed to clean and restore our coastlines without harming the environment.

Unlike existing cleanup technology, the BeBot is 100% electric and runs on a mix of solar and battery power. Meaning it doesn't require fuel and has no harmful emissions, smelly diesel fumes, or noise pollution. The BeBot is completely safe for the local environment and wildlife!

To learn more about the BeBot, which was designed by robotic engineers and deployed by @Poralu_Marine, visit the link in our bio.

#4ocean #robot #robotics #technology #innovation

As we tackle plastic pollution around the world, Team Guatemala has been making huge strides on this 25-mile stretch of polluted coastline!

Back in July, we began showing you footage of this immensely polluted coastline in Guatemala. The mounds of plastic were caused by heavy inland rains, which caused trash to wash into the Motagua River, where it flowed into the ocean and back onto Guatemala's shore. 

Since then, our crews have been tackling this coastline and have been making a big impact. Over 20,000 pounds of trash were collected within the first 30 days, most of which was single-use plastic.

Help us continue to clean up this mess by pulling a pound of trash at 4ocean.com
